context: At the begin of the <b7_0>Holocene<b7_0/> (<a0_1><a0_2>~<a0_0><b4_0><b6_0>11,700 years ago<b6_0/><b4_0/><a0_2/><a0_1/><a0_0/>), the Rhine occupied its <a1_0><a1_1><a1_2>Late-Glacial valley<a1_2/><a1_1/><a1_0/>. As a meandering river, it reworked its ice-age braidplain. As sea-level continued to rise in the <a2_0><a2_1><a2_2>Netherlands<a2_2/><a2_1/><a2_0/>, the formation of the Holocene Rhine-Meuse delta began (<a3_1><a3_2>~<a3_0><b5_0>8,000 years ago<b5_0/><a3_2/><a3_1/><a3_0/>). Coeval absolute sea-level rise and tectonic subsidence have strongly influenced delta evolution. Other factors of importance to the shape of the delta are the local tectonic activities of the Peel Boundary Fault, the substrate and geomorphology, as inherited from the Last Glacial and the coastal-marine dynamics, such as barrier and tidal inlet formations.
